WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.120
Tyler Fisher: Hello, all right, start over for the

00:00:05.120 --> 00:00:06.240
stream.

00:00:06.250 --> 00:00:07.400
Hello, I'm Tyler Fisher.

00:00:07.460 --> 00:00:10.160
I make a project called SIL, which is a client

00:00:10.160 --> 00:00:12.200
on top of the blue sky post lexicon that aggreg

00:00:12.580 --> 00:00:15.050
ates the top links in your network.

00:00:15.220 --> 00:00:18.530
It's a unique client experience that nothing else in the atmosphere

00:00:18.530 --> 00:00:20.240
offers right now.

00:00:20.240 --> 00:00:22.560
And I think we need more unique types of clients.

00:00:22.560 --> 00:00:25.610
So I'm going to talk about how we can achieve that

00:00:26.060 --> 00:00:26.640
today.

00:00:26.660 --> 00:00:29.180
Last year, I moved to Harlem, a small city in

00:00:29.180 --> 00:00:30.700
the Netherlands.

00:00:30.780 --> 00:00:32.100
At the center of the city, we have the Hr

00:00:32.100 --> 00:00:35.810
ultenmarkt, a large public plaza that is overlooked

00:00:35.810 --> 00:00:38.340
by the Sint Babelkerk, the giant church

00:00:38.740 --> 00:00:38.900
.

00:00:38.900 --> 00:00:42.310
It's a grand plaza that on the weekends turns into

00:00:42.310 --> 00:00:45.230
a public square for local vendors.

00:00:45.230 --> 00:00:48.840
But at any time during the week, it's a lovely

00:00:48.840 --> 00:00:49.800
place to be.

00:00:49.800 --> 00:00:52.200
It's quiet, safe, comfortable.

00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:55.190
You'll also notice in this photo, it's car free

00:00:55.640 --> 00:00:55.700
.

00:00:55.780 --> 00:00:58.760
The Netherlands is famous for its pedestrian and bicycle infrastructure.

00:00:58.760 --> 00:01:00.660
But it wasn't always this way.

00:01:00.760 --> 00:01:03.480
The Hrultenmarkt in the 1960s was more

00:01:03.480 --> 00:01:06.490
of a parking lot and a road and a traffic circle going

00:01:06.580 --> 00:01:07.040
through it.

00:01:07.080 --> 00:01:11.000
When visitors visit the Hrultenmarkt today, they

00:01:11.300 --> 00:01:14.180
tend to think of it as it's always been this way

00:01:14.180 --> 00:01:14.480
.

00:01:14.480 --> 00:01:16.960
This is an ancient public square that's been this way since

00:01:17.060 --> 00:01:17.760
the 1300s.

00:01:18.020 --> 00:01:19.480
But it's not true.

00:01:19.610 --> 00:01:23.040
The Hrultenmarkt was transformed as a result of

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:28.000
sustained protest and community engagement in Harlem during the 1960s and

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:30.300
70s to rip out the roads, rip out the parking

00:01:30.300 --> 00:01:32.270
, and make it a pedestrianized plaza.

00:01:32.300 --> 00:01:36.530
This got me thinking about how cities transform to places that are

00:01:36.940 --> 00:01:40.160
designed more for people and what we can learn from walkable

00:01:40.160 --> 00:01:42.680
cities about transforming digital spaces.

00:01:43.050 --> 00:01:48.270
Ultimately, walkable cities are about getting people to walk or

00:01:48.270 --> 00:01:52.130
take some other form of mobility to their destination instead of driving

00:01:52.230 --> 00:01:53.000
a car.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:56.370
The American city planner, Jeff Speck, gave a talk

00:01:56.380 --> 00:01:59.820
in 2013 about building walkable cities.

00:01:59.820 --> 00:02:03.800
He says that a walk has to offer four things for somebody

00:02:04.150 --> 00:02:07.350
to walk or take some other form of mobility instead of drive

00:02:07.350 --> 00:02:07.520
.

00:02:07.520 --> 00:02:09.870
And I saw for these four things simultaneously.

00:02:10.240 --> 00:02:12.420
There needs to be a proper reason to walk.

00:02:12.420 --> 00:02:14.550
The walk has to be safe and feel safe.

00:02:14.760 --> 00:02:16.440
The walk has to be comfortable.

00:02:16.590 --> 00:02:18.300
And the walk has to be interesting.

00:02:18.300 --> 00:02:21.740
I, like many of you, have been thinking about how

00:02:21.750 --> 00:02:23.820
do we grow the atmosphere.

00:02:24.070 --> 00:02:27.910
Building the atmosphere is an infrastructural change to the internet

00:02:28.360 --> 00:02:31.810
on the level of transforming a city from one that is car

00:02:31.810 --> 00:02:34.560
-centric to one that is person-centric.

00:02:34.710 --> 00:02:38.290
So in thinking about this problem, I found myself revisiting

00:02:38.300 --> 00:02:40.550
Speck's theory, but for the atmosphere.

00:02:40.550 --> 00:02:43.660
There needs to be a proper reason to join the atmosphere.

00:02:43.660 --> 00:02:46.090
The atmosphere has to be safe and feel safe.

00:02:46.350 --> 00:02:48.620
The atmosphere has to be comfortable.

00:02:48.620 --> 00:02:50.860
And the atmosphere has to be interesting.

00:02:50.860 --> 00:02:53.620
We can break this theory into four parts.

00:02:53.620 --> 00:02:56.440
Purpose, a proper reason to join the atmosphere.

00:02:57.340 --> 00:03:00.290
Safety, the atmosphere has to be safe and feel safe.

00:03:00.480 --> 00:03:02.620
Comfort, the atmosphere has to be comfortable.

00:03:02.620 --> 00:03:05.660
And interest, the atmosphere has to be interesting.

00:03:05.760 --> 00:03:09.000
I'd like to propose this four-component framing as

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:13.110
a structure for how we think about building atmospheric clients.

00:03:13.240 --> 00:03:15.600
In this talk, I'm going to walk through each of

00:03:15.600 --> 00:03:18.250
these four components and what they mean for client design.

00:03:18.250 --> 00:03:20.330
I'll talk about how I think about them in my own

00:03:20.330 --> 00:03:23.730
projects and offer some inspiration from elsewhere in the atmosphere that I

00:03:23.730 --> 00:03:28.340
think do some of these things particularly well and discuss what opportunities

00:03:28.340 --> 00:03:32.820
I see for us to further atmospheric clients in these four directions

00:03:32.820 --> 00:03:33.020
.

00:03:33.020 --> 00:03:35.180
Let's start with purpose.

00:03:35.190 --> 00:03:38.950
Speck's original theory describes us as having a proper reason

00:03:38.950 --> 00:03:39.550
to walk.

00:03:39.550 --> 00:03:42.450
For this, he means having a destination in mind.

00:03:42.450 --> 00:03:45.610
For a walkable city, you have to have schools and

00:03:45.880 --> 00:03:50.060
doctors, restaurants, bars, grocery stores, everything you need

00:03:50.060 --> 00:03:51.950
within walking distance.

00:03:51.950 --> 00:03:55.410
We're all here building new apps, new experiences, trying

00:03:55.530 --> 00:03:58.180
to entice people to join the open social web.

00:03:58.180 --> 00:03:59.370
But why would they?

00:03:59.630 --> 00:04:04.060
Often we lead with pitches about dated sovereignty, privacy, openness

00:04:04.060 --> 00:04:06.040
, and while these are critical features, it's why we

00:04:06.180 --> 00:04:06.700
're all here.

00:04:06.700 --> 00:04:09.950
They should be a given for atmospheric applications.

00:04:09.950 --> 00:04:11.750
People need more purpose than that.

00:04:11.930 --> 00:04:14.700
It's not enough to build the pedestrianized streets of the

00:04:14.700 --> 00:04:15.560
internet.

00:04:15.560 --> 00:04:17.430
They have to go somewhere.

00:04:17.700 --> 00:04:21.720
The inability to convince people to join new social networks is a

00:04:21.720 --> 00:04:22.990
long study problem.

00:04:22.990 --> 00:04:24.390
Switching costs are real.

00:04:24.840 --> 00:04:28.060
People won't move unless their network has already moved.

00:04:28.060 --> 00:04:29.900
We can't solve this problem overnight.

00:04:30.280 --> 00:04:34.530
What's exciting about AT Proto is the opportunities offered by

00:04:34.530 --> 00:04:35.090
the PDS.

00:04:35.090 --> 00:04:38.260
There have been over 40 million signups for Blue Sky so

00:04:38.400 --> 00:04:40.130
far, each with their own PDS.

00:04:40.950 --> 00:04:43.320
Each of those already have an account with your app too.

00:04:43.320 --> 00:04:45.600
But if you're offering your own experience and your own le

00:04:45.600 --> 00:04:48.230
xicon separate from the Blue Sky experience, this is somewhat

00:04:48.450 --> 00:04:48.830
cold comfort.

00:04:49.200 --> 00:04:53.150
40 million people can sign into your app, but if there

00:04:53.320 --> 00:04:56.840
is no real content and their people aren't on your le

00:04:56.840 --> 00:04:58.860
xicons yet, there's not going to be much for

00:04:58.860 --> 00:04:59.660
them to engage with.

00:04:59.660 --> 00:05:04.260
So how can we leverage the Blue Sky existing network, but

00:05:04.260 --> 00:05:08.780
offer new experiences that offer new motivations to join the atmosphere?

00:05:08.780 --> 00:05:12.640
One option is to build clients on top of the existing le

00:05:12.640 --> 00:05:14.270
xicons, but offer new experiences.

00:05:14.440 --> 00:05:16.040
And that's what I've done with Sill, my

00:05:16.040 --> 00:05:18.670
link aggregation client that is built on top of Blue Sky

00:05:18.760 --> 00:05:19.570
and Mastodon.

00:05:19.970 --> 00:05:24.470
Sill reads your following timeline, finds the most popular links

00:05:24.680 --> 00:05:27.710
in your network, and offers you a different picture of your

00:05:27.710 --> 00:05:31.650
feed by rank ordering the most popular links in your network.

00:05:31.650 --> 00:05:36.050
It's most common use case for people is as a news

00:05:36.050 --> 00:05:36.610
reader.

00:05:36.610 --> 00:05:39.820
Typically, the most commonly shared URLs are news stories.

00:05:40.270 --> 00:05:44.270
Many people use social media for news, and Sill offers

00:05:44.440 --> 00:05:46.320
them an optimized way to do so.

00:05:46.320 --> 00:05:49.450
This is a new experience built on top of an existing le

00:05:49.450 --> 00:05:49.980
xicon.

00:05:49.980 --> 00:05:51.370
But Sill's read-only.

00:05:51.370 --> 00:05:54.980
What if you wanted to offer a whole new social experience without

00:05:54.980 --> 00:05:57.260
having to bootstrap a whole new lexicon?

00:05:57.260 --> 00:06:01.630
Sebastian Vogelsang's Flashes offers a really compelling concept

00:06:01.630 --> 00:06:02.010
here.

00:06:02.010 --> 00:06:04.620
It's a photo sharing app akin to Instagram, but it

00:06:04.620 --> 00:06:07.980
uses the Blue Sky Post lexicon as its root.

00:06:07.980 --> 00:06:12.050
But rather than limit itself to the limitations of the Post le

00:06:12.050 --> 00:06:15.130
xicon in terms of photo sharing, it adds sidecar

00:06:15.380 --> 00:06:19.570
records on top of the Blue Sky Post so that in the

00:06:19.580 --> 00:06:22.810
Flashes app you get a more full photo sharing experience.

00:06:23.060 --> 00:06:26.460
But Blue Sky users can still see and interact with those posts

00:06:26.460 --> 00:06:30.180
, so you're immediately getting the benefit of being on the

00:06:30.220 --> 00:06:33.580
atmosphere while still offering a new experience.

00:06:33.580 --> 00:06:37.830
So now the atmosphere as a whole has two separate experiences to

00:06:37.830 --> 00:06:40.560
offer people, microblogging, and photo sharing, and

00:06:40.560 --> 00:06:44.210
they're seamlessly connected, letting everyone take advantage of the increasingly

00:06:44.210 --> 00:06:45.180
growing social graph.

00:06:45.180 --> 00:06:49.090
As the atmosphere grows, more lexicons will get adopted

00:06:49.190 --> 00:06:52.670
, offering more opportunities for extension, remixing, and combination

00:06:53.040 --> 00:06:54.770
from the client experience.

00:06:55.020 --> 00:06:57.710
The community developing around standard outside is bearing a ton of fruit

00:06:57.710 --> 00:06:58.040
here.

00:06:58.060 --> 00:07:01.390
In the long form space, I would love to see more

00:07:01.500 --> 00:07:04.860
work around premium news reading experiences.

00:07:05.500 --> 00:07:08.520
There's both a supply and demand problem here of getting news

00:07:08.680 --> 00:07:11.350
onto protocol and getting readers to understand that there is news on

00:07:11.350 --> 00:07:11.980
the protocol.

00:07:11.980 --> 00:07:14.940
I'm going to talk more about news on ATProto

00:07:14.940 --> 00:07:16.210
at a panel tomorrow at 10 a.

00:07:16.210 --> 00:07:16.370
m.

00:07:16.370 --> 00:07:18.460
if you want to hear me talk more about that specifically.

00:07:18.460 --> 00:07:23.040
But back to Speck's theory, he says that Walk

00:07:23.230 --> 00:07:24.940
must be safe and feel safe.

00:07:25.080 --> 00:07:26.940
This phrasing is specific.

00:07:26.940 --> 00:07:29.210
There are, in fact, two related things here: being

00:07:29.470 --> 00:07:31.580
safe and feeling safe.

00:07:31.710 --> 00:07:34.230
It's an important distinction and one we have to think about

00:07:34.230 --> 00:07:35.360
as we design digital spaces.

00:07:35.630 --> 00:07:39.580
When you first talk about safety in digital spaces, the first

00:07:39.580 --> 00:07:41.500
thing you're going to think of is content moderation.

00:07:41.500 --> 00:07:45.530
I have no personal experience with content moderation.

00:07:45.530 --> 00:07:48.350
It's not something I do instill beyond allowing people to

00:07:48.690 --> 00:07:50.610
mute words and domains and accounts.

00:07:50.610 --> 00:07:52.920
I'm just not an expert, so I'm not going

00:07:53.020 --> 00:07:56.650
to say much about content moderation today, and I'd rather

00:07:56.650 --> 00:07:58.140
point you to the experts in the space.

00:07:58.360 --> 00:08:02.160
Black Sky just released Acorn, which is a community moderation

00:08:02.160 --> 00:08:05.550
tool that they built with prioritizing the health of the moder

00:08:05.550 --> 00:08:06.140
ators.

00:08:06.270 --> 00:08:09.250
And I think that's a really awesome approach.

00:08:09.250 --> 00:08:11.740
The team at Roost has released Osprey, which

00:08:11.740 --> 00:08:15.990
is a more automated approach to dealing with abuse on social media

00:08:16.440 --> 00:08:19.900
and automating that moderation burden.

00:08:19.900 --> 00:08:23.500
And then research by Aaron Kassane and Darius Kaz

00:08:23.500 --> 00:08:24.900
emi from a few years ago.

00:08:24.900 --> 00:08:28.320
They did research on moderation in the Fediverse and composable

00:08:28.320 --> 00:08:28.970
moderation.

00:08:28.970 --> 00:08:30.970
It is about the Fediverse, but I think it offers

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:33.440
a ton of lessons as we think about this in the atmosphere

00:08:33.440 --> 00:08:33.980
as well.

00:08:33.980 --> 00:08:37.980
I want to tackle safety from a different angle, which is

00:08:37.980 --> 00:08:41.940
how can our social media clients encourage healthier social media habits?

00:08:42.080 --> 00:08:44.310
After all, even in a well-moderated network

00:08:44.310 --> 00:08:45.690
, we can become addicted.

00:08:45.690 --> 00:08:47.780
When the news is bad, we can fall prey to doom

00:08:47.810 --> 00:08:48.550
scrolling.

00:08:48.670 --> 00:08:52.510
Even with reverse chronological timelines or algorithmic timelines, the

00:08:52.680 --> 00:08:57.640
context collapse of different topics matched together can overwhelm and confuse

00:08:57.640 --> 00:08:58.140
us.

00:08:58.160 --> 00:09:01.500
With Sill, I want to find solutions to these problems

00:09:01.500 --> 00:09:01.500
.

00:09:01.500 --> 00:09:04.520
By default, Sill aggregates to the top links in

00:09:04.680 --> 00:09:06.860
your network over 24 hours.

00:09:06.860 --> 00:09:08.810
So if you leave it at that default, Sill doesn

00:09:08.810 --> 00:09:10.710
't actually change very much throughout the day.

00:09:10.940 --> 00:09:13.850
And this is actually a good thing if your primary use case

00:09:13.850 --> 00:09:16.090
for social media is reading news.

00:09:16.090 --> 00:09:18.970
Your network will surface the news that matters.

00:09:18.970 --> 00:09:21.470
And once it reaches you, there's going to be a

00:09:21.480 --> 00:09:25.040
ton of context from your network helping you process it, helping

00:09:25.040 --> 00:09:26.090
you understand it.

00:09:26.350 --> 00:09:29.900
As the story develops, you don't need to continue scrolling

00:09:30.060 --> 00:09:32.660
your timeline where only every tenth post is actually the thing you

00:09:32.660 --> 00:09:34.290
're trying to learn about right now.

00:09:35.740 --> 00:09:39.050
Sill groups it all together, keeping your mind focused and

00:09:39.050 --> 00:09:43.010
allowing you to read the story and grapple with its ram

00:09:43.010 --> 00:09:47.250
ifications without jumping to another topic and switching contexts.

00:09:47.340 --> 00:09:50.670
Sill's -- these tactics are working with Sill's

00:09:51.040 --> 00:09:55.510
users who regularly report that it's helping them use social media

00:09:55.510 --> 00:09:57.790
less while still staying engaged.

00:09:58.160 --> 00:10:02.750
David Crespo says he stays logged out of Blue Sky

00:10:02.810 --> 00:10:04.540
on his phone and only uses Sill on his phone.

00:10:05.240 --> 00:10:09.060
Robinson Meyer says he can dip in and out throughout the day

00:10:09.080 --> 00:10:09.080
.

00:10:09.180 --> 00:10:12.300
David Ziff says if you want to use Blue Sky to

00:10:12.360 --> 00:10:15.780
follow the news but you find feeds overwhelming, Sill is

00:10:15.780 --> 00:10:17.340
a good alternative to that.

00:10:17.640 --> 00:10:23.580
This is giving users a lever of control over their experience,

00:10:23.580 --> 00:10:26.780
and this contributes to them feeling safe in the atmosphere.

00:10:29.180 --> 00:10:32.510
What other modalities can we offer in the atmosphere that offer

00:10:32.590 --> 00:10:36.330
a more controlled experience over social media?

00:10:36.330 --> 00:10:40.740
I really love Anasota, which turns Blue Sky into

00:10:40.740 --> 00:10:45.220
a card swipe-based experience and layers on like a m

00:10:45.220 --> 00:10:49.340
oth collecting game and all kinds of really neat artistic approaches to

00:10:49.340 --> 00:10:49.970
social media.

00:10:49.980 --> 00:10:53.320
It also has similar motivations to Sill of calm and focus

00:10:53.680 --> 00:10:57.080
rather than the real-time drip feed of social media,

00:10:57.080 --> 00:10:58.770
traditional social media design.

00:10:58.880 --> 00:11:00.850
It has a stamina meter, so if you swipe too much

00:11:00.860 --> 00:11:02.970
, it tells you you got to stop, you're out

00:11:03.080 --> 00:11:03.590
of stamina.

00:11:03.820 --> 00:11:06.420
I think it's really brilliant and offers a ton of things

00:11:06.420 --> 00:11:06.780
to learn.

00:11:06.780 --> 00:11:12.700
Overall, how else can we help users to leverage the collective

00:11:12.700 --> 00:11:16.750
intelligence of their networks without forcing them into the same tired designs

00:11:16.750 --> 00:11:19.690
that we've been using for social media for the last two

00:11:19.690 --> 00:11:20.140
decades?

00:11:20.140 --> 00:11:23.470
We've spent enough time with both chronological timelines and algorithm

00:11:23.470 --> 00:11:26.170
ic timelines to know the problems well, so it's time

00:11:26.170 --> 00:11:29.530
to move beyond these and offer new experiences for people that give

00:11:29.530 --> 00:11:32.610
them control and help them feel safe in the atmosphere.

00:11:32.620 --> 00:11:35.580
Back to our walkable cities analogy, Speck says the

00:11:35.800 --> 00:11:37.420
walk has to be comfortable.

00:11:37.420 --> 00:11:41.130
In the physical space, that can mean quiet roads, accessible

00:11:41.200 --> 00:11:43.420
crosswalks, well-paid paths.

00:11:43.420 --> 00:11:45.690
In the digital space, I think about comfort as meeting people

00:11:45.950 --> 00:11:49.600
where they are, as joining the atmosphere should not require a

00:11:49.790 --> 00:11:52.450
downgrade to their user experience, and this is a really

00:11:52.450 --> 00:11:53.180
tall task.

00:11:53.180 --> 00:11:55.570
We're going to have to stretch ourselves.

00:11:55.570 --> 00:11:58.890
Many of us, myself included, are believers in the web

00:11:59.150 --> 00:12:02.050
over native apps, but it's undeniable that users

00:12:02.050 --> 00:12:05.110
prefer and expect native apps, especially on their phones.

00:12:05.560 --> 00:12:10.130
With sale, the number one question I get when I tell

00:12:10.140 --> 00:12:12.870
people less online than me about it is, how do I

00:12:12.870 --> 00:12:14.370
get it in the app store?

00:12:14.370 --> 00:12:16.620
It's a website.

00:12:16.620 --> 00:12:18.630
I say, just put it in your web browser, sale

00:12:18.630 --> 00:12:18.800
.

00:12:19.080 --> 00:12:19.420
social.

00:12:19.420 --> 00:12:21.510
At that point, I lose a lot of people.

00:12:21.630 --> 00:12:23.660
They might try it once while I'm there in the room

00:12:23.660 --> 00:12:24.270
with them.

00:12:24.380 --> 00:12:26.090
If I see them a week later, I ask them how

00:12:26.090 --> 00:12:27.950
it's going, and they haven't gone back.

00:12:27.950 --> 00:12:29.050
They don't think about it.

00:12:29.250 --> 00:12:30.780
They're not in the web browser that way.

00:12:30.780 --> 00:12:33.930
I'd show them how you can add it to your home

00:12:33.960 --> 00:12:34.780
screen.

00:12:34.780 --> 00:12:37.460
SIL is a progressive web app, but after walking through

00:12:37.460 --> 00:12:41.340
that menu diving and explaining the differences between progressive web apps and

00:12:41.340 --> 00:12:43.340
native apps, I've already lost them.

00:12:43.340 --> 00:12:45.690
They just want to be able to install it from the app

00:12:45.690 --> 00:12:46.350
store.

00:12:46.350 --> 00:12:48.890
So I built an iOS app for SIL that's now

00:12:48.890 --> 00:12:50.980
in testing, and if you want to get on the test

00:12:50.980 --> 00:12:52.600
flight, here's the QR code.

00:12:52.660 --> 00:12:54.890
I hope to build an Android app after I get through the

00:12:54.890 --> 00:12:56.800
launch process at the iOS app.

00:12:56.800 --> 00:13:00.040
Over half of SIL's web traffic comes from iOS users

00:13:00.040 --> 00:13:01.650
, so that's why I started with iOS.

00:13:01.650 --> 00:13:03.960
And begrudgingly, I actually do now see how

00:13:03.960 --> 00:13:06.810
a fully native app for SIL offers some real benefits for

00:13:06.810 --> 00:13:07.610
those users.

00:13:07.610 --> 00:13:10.790
With deep OS integration, I can offer push notifications.

00:13:10.910 --> 00:13:15.330
This takes SIL's notification feature that already existed to its

00:13:15.400 --> 00:13:16.620
natural conclusion, right?

00:13:16.870 --> 00:13:19.940
Now SIL can tell you, based on parameters you define

00:13:20.090 --> 00:13:23.150
, SIL can send you a push notification when news is

00:13:23.180 --> 00:13:26.710
emerging in your network, and it can find you when it

00:13:27.160 --> 00:13:27.900
happens.

00:13:27.900 --> 00:13:31.660
Sorry, I lost myself.

00:13:31.660 --> 00:13:35.020
It can offer widgets, giving you a quick at-a

00:13:35.020 --> 00:13:39.260
-glance view of the top link in your network without

00:13:39.270 --> 00:13:41.380
ever having to really even open the app.

00:13:41.380 --> 00:13:43.500
I can offer a native share target.

00:13:43.590 --> 00:13:45.400
SIL also does bookmarking.

00:13:45.450 --> 00:13:48.790
So with the native share target, you can bookmark a

00:13:48.790 --> 00:13:51.830
link from anywhere you experience it within the operating system.

00:13:53.820 --> 00:13:55.980
It is currently in beta, and you can, yeah,

00:13:56.040 --> 00:13:58.080
join the Tesla if you would like, and let me know

00:13:58.130 --> 00:13:59.030
how it goes.

00:13:59.030 --> 00:14:00.830
I'd love your feedback.

00:14:00.990 --> 00:14:05.290
For all of big tech's faults and misalignments

00:14:05.290 --> 00:14:08.530
, they offer a comfortable experience to users.

00:14:08.680 --> 00:14:11.910
They employ legions of people to focus exclusively on user experience

00:14:12.370 --> 00:14:13.740
, and they do it on every platform.

00:14:13.740 --> 00:14:16.630
Web, iOS, Android, and more.

00:14:16.660 --> 00:14:20.000
Many of us in the atmosphere, myself included, our founders

00:14:20.150 --> 00:14:22.620
, our solo founders, or small teams.

00:14:22.750 --> 00:14:26.870
Somehow we have to deliver on better user experiences for people with

00:14:26.870 --> 00:14:28.180
far fewer resources.

00:14:28.200 --> 00:14:29.820
But here's our advantage.

00:14:29.820 --> 00:14:33.470
For all big tech's resources, to throw at user experience

00:14:33.590 --> 00:14:36.200
, they often throw them at misaligned ends, mis

00:14:36.200 --> 00:14:38.620
aligned with the interest of the everyday user.

00:14:38.620 --> 00:14:42.670
If we as a community can stay aligned on centering user

00:14:42.670 --> 00:14:47.090
needs and furthering the vision that we all have of a

00:14:47.090 --> 00:14:50.840
better internet, we can collectively offer a better experience than our

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:51.900
competition.

00:14:51.900 --> 00:14:55.640
I'm inspired by the interoperability story offered by Sem

00:14:55.640 --> 00:14:56.810
ble and Margin.

00:14:56.830 --> 00:15:01.700
Semble is a sense-making tool letting you collect collections

00:15:01.760 --> 00:15:04.910
of bookmarks and blue sky posts and other things around the

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:05.150
web.

00:15:05.300 --> 00:15:07.660
And you can organize them into various collections.

00:15:07.660 --> 00:15:09.130
You can do that individually.

00:15:09.130 --> 00:15:12.460
You can do that in a public collection together with people in

00:15:12.460 --> 00:15:13.090
the atmosphere.

00:15:13.100 --> 00:15:16.600
Margin is an annotation layer for the web where you add

00:15:16.800 --> 00:15:20.570
comments and annotations to any web page and save that annotation

00:15:20.570 --> 00:15:21.350
to your PDS.

00:15:21.350 --> 00:15:25.330
They're working together so that you can -- your bookmarks

00:15:25.630 --> 00:15:28.690
from either Margin or Semble both work within both tools

00:15:28.690 --> 00:15:29.980
as you're using them.

00:15:29.980 --> 00:15:35.000
So that allows Semble to focus on where its innovation is

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:38.200
in the shared collections and organizational tools.

00:15:38.560 --> 00:15:42.030
And Margin can focus on its innovation of being able to

00:15:42.030 --> 00:15:43.500
annotate anything on the web.

00:15:43.640 --> 00:15:46.300
But they all work together and they make each other better.

00:15:46.300 --> 00:15:47.950
And it's not a competitive experience.

00:15:47.950 --> 00:15:49.500
It's a collaborative experience.

00:15:49.500 --> 00:15:54.670
We need more shared infrastructure in order to pull things off like

00:15:54.700 --> 00:15:55.180
this.

00:15:55.180 --> 00:15:57.190
Depending on your use case, it could be really hard to

00:15:57.190 --> 00:15:59.340
mix and match lexicons in the atmosphere right now,

00:15:59.400 --> 00:16:01.620
especially if one of the lexons you want to use

00:16:01.620 --> 00:16:02.580
is a blue sky one.

00:16:02.590 --> 00:16:05.350
Now you're talking about indexing terabytes of data if

00:16:05.350 --> 00:16:07.020
you want a full network backfill.

00:16:07.160 --> 00:16:11.420
So I love things like the microcosm set of tools

00:16:11.500 --> 00:16:14.470
offer a ton of really easy ways for people to jump in

00:16:14.680 --> 00:16:18.410
and pull different records from throughout the atmosphere.

00:16:18.410 --> 00:16:20.910
I'd like to see more tools that offer more use cases

00:16:21.110 --> 00:16:21.290
.

00:16:21.290 --> 00:16:24.780
Something I'd really love to see is a network-wide

00:16:24.780 --> 00:16:29.040
app view that's designed for aggregative workloads, by which

00:16:29.040 --> 00:16:32.550
I mean, you know, group by the types of fundamentally

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:34.860
database queries that SIL is doing, right?

00:16:34.860 --> 00:16:37.760
Grouping by link, grouping by tangled star.

00:16:37.760 --> 00:16:42.310
You can find links within leaflet docs, standard site docs

00:16:42.370 --> 00:16:42.700
.

00:16:42.700 --> 00:16:46.350
I think it opens up a ton of interesting opportunities for experiences

00:16:46.460 --> 00:16:49.470
that collect the whole atmosphere and not just focus on one app

00:16:49.470 --> 00:16:50.140
experience.

00:16:50.830 --> 00:16:57.800
Our last component, interest, is maybe the most surprising when

00:16:57.810 --> 00:17:00.120
you think about walkable cities for specs components.

00:17:00.270 --> 00:17:02.140
But for the atmosphere, I think it's probably the most

00:17:02.140 --> 00:17:03.210
obvious one, right?

00:17:03.210 --> 00:17:05.170
We have to build into interesting things.

00:17:05.270 --> 00:17:08.250
We're competing with the whole internet for everybody's time and

00:17:08.250 --> 00:17:09.150
we have to win.

00:17:09.320 --> 00:17:12.530
What sticks out to me when I think about making interesting things

00:17:12.940 --> 00:17:15.310
around the atmosphere is they have to be interesting immediately.

00:17:15.460 --> 00:17:19.170
This is a place where I think the client experience can do

00:17:19.170 --> 00:17:21.790
a lot of work, even if you're not interested in

00:17:21.790 --> 00:17:23.580
developing new lexicons.

00:17:23.580 --> 00:17:25.840
But to do it right is going to take some coordinated effort

00:17:26.110 --> 00:17:26.300
.

00:17:26.300 --> 00:17:29.010
Let's use SIL as an example of what I mean

00:17:29.110 --> 00:17:29.420
.

00:17:29.420 --> 00:17:31.610
With SIL, I've been thinking about how to onboard

00:17:31.640 --> 00:17:35.360
people into the atmosphere if they don't already have a PD

00:17:35.360 --> 00:17:35.810
S.

00:17:35.810 --> 00:17:41.500
And I want to point them in the direction of trustworthy news

00:17:41.640 --> 00:17:43.950
that matches their needs and interests.

00:17:43.950 --> 00:17:46.070
Today's SIL only really works if you've invested time

00:17:46.210 --> 00:17:49.460
in building your own network and your following graph so that it

00:17:49.460 --> 00:17:52.140
is a trusted network of information that you'd like.

00:17:52.140 --> 00:17:55.810
For people in this room, that's probably pretty easy to

00:17:55.810 --> 00:17:56.060
do.

00:17:56.060 --> 00:17:58.240
But for new users, that's a really tough hurdle to

00:17:58.240 --> 00:17:58.690
climb.

00:18:00.060 --> 00:18:01.800
People need help finding people.

00:18:01.800 --> 00:18:04.310
And while it had some flaws, one of, I think

00:18:04.370 --> 00:18:09.110
, the key parts of growth of Blue Sky's 2024 post

00:18:09.250 --> 00:18:12.300
-election growth was the starter pack.

00:18:12.560 --> 00:18:15.810
And it was received well enough that the competition copied it.

00:18:15.810 --> 00:18:17.830
Meta has starter packs and threads.

00:18:17.830 --> 00:18:21.530
Blue Sky's other competitive edge is custom fees and algorithmic

00:18:21.530 --> 00:18:22.100
choice.

00:18:22.120 --> 00:18:24.700
Combining these two things, we can bootstrap a

00:18:24.700 --> 00:18:28.090
user's network based on their interests rather quickly.

00:18:28.350 --> 00:18:29.630
This is not live in SIL yet.

00:18:29.630 --> 00:18:30.860
I haven't started building.

00:18:30.860 --> 00:18:33.000
But here's how I see a SIL possible onboarding

00:18:33.080 --> 00:18:34.190
experience working.

00:18:34.560 --> 00:18:37.760
Users without an atmosphere account can register with a PDS.

00:18:37.760 --> 00:18:39.390
SIL doesn't need to run that PDS.

00:18:39.510 --> 00:18:40.860
I don't want to run a PDS.

00:18:40.860 --> 00:18:44.470
But I'm open to partnering with anybody who is operating a

00:18:44.620 --> 00:18:48.080
PDS and thinks something like this would be interesting to host

00:18:48.080 --> 00:18:48.860
new users.

00:18:48.860 --> 00:18:51.610
And I'd especially love if it wasn't Blue Sky so

00:18:51.610 --> 00:18:55.100
that we can further the decentralization story of the atmosphere at

00:18:55.260 --> 00:18:55.830
the same time.

00:18:56.280 --> 00:18:59.950
After they register with the PDS, they can come back

00:18:59.950 --> 00:19:02.280
to SIL and tell SIL a bit about what publications

00:19:02.650 --> 00:19:04.920
they read, what topics they're interested in.

00:19:04.920 --> 00:19:07.550
And through a combination of starter packs lists and custom feeds,

00:19:07.660 --> 00:19:10.040
they can immediately bootstrap their graph.

00:19:10.040 --> 00:19:12.060
And then SIL is ready and useful on day one as

00:19:12.080 --> 00:19:14.420
soon as they finish that process.

00:19:14.420 --> 00:19:16.980
And they can go over to the Blue Sky app or whatever

00:19:16.980 --> 00:19:17.770
other client.

00:19:17.770 --> 00:19:20.050
And it's already set up and ready to go.

00:19:20.050 --> 00:19:23.580
But maybe you see the problem with this idea.

00:19:23.580 --> 00:19:27.210
It requires maintaining a complex set of feeds, lists, and

00:19:27.210 --> 00:19:28.160
starter packs.

00:19:28.420 --> 00:19:32.610
Keeping all those maintained over time as people leave and join the

00:19:32.620 --> 00:19:34.770
network, it would become my full-time job if I

00:19:34.840 --> 00:19:35.950
was going to do that alone.

00:19:36.030 --> 00:19:37.780
I wouldn't be able to work on the app.

00:19:37.780 --> 00:19:39.260
I would just work on maintaining feeds.

00:19:39.260 --> 00:19:44.200
So making sense of the Blue Sky Social Graph has many uses

00:19:44.200 --> 00:19:45.400
for many applications.

00:19:45.400 --> 00:19:48.110
So this is something I think we could maybe take a collective

00:19:48.110 --> 00:19:52.190
approach to and trying to find the bubbles that exist already.

00:19:52.270 --> 00:19:55.580
I know there's been some mapping projects that people have done

00:19:55.580 --> 00:19:57.380
, and I wonder if we can build on top of those

00:19:57.400 --> 00:20:00.260
to automate some starter packs and some feeds and point people in

00:20:00.260 --> 00:20:02.670
the right direction as soon as they get started.

00:20:03.040 --> 00:20:07.300
Sports, I think, offer a really unique opportunity here.

00:20:07.300 --> 00:20:09.750
A lot of Blue Sky, my understanding is a lot of

00:20:09.750 --> 00:20:13.240
Blue Sky's post-2024 growth has come from sports

00:20:13.240 --> 00:20:13.420
.

00:20:13.420 --> 00:20:16.760
Usage tends to peak around major American sporting events like the

00:20:16.820 --> 00:20:18.360
World Series and Super Bowl.

00:20:18.360 --> 00:20:22.370
But sports are also a place where X and other social networks

00:20:23.190 --> 00:20:24.720
maintain a strong foothold.

00:20:24.720 --> 00:20:27.730
So how can we use community-driven feeds and starter packs

00:20:27.750 --> 00:20:32.970
to easily onboard people with the already vibrant sports network that Blue

00:20:33.230 --> 00:20:33.660
Sky has?

00:20:33.860 --> 00:20:37.630
And how might we use those networks to encourage activity and the

00:20:37.630 --> 00:20:39.190
atmosphere overall?

00:20:39.390 --> 00:20:42.700
I can imagine onboarding clients that ask you what's your

00:20:42.710 --> 00:20:45.880
favorite team and then just setting up your graph immediately based on

00:20:46.110 --> 00:20:48.110
your favorite teams and favorite leagues.

00:20:48.140 --> 00:20:52.390
Transforming the internet from the walled gardens of Web 2

00:20:52.450 --> 00:20:52.650
.

00:20:52.770 --> 00:20:55.900
0 to the openness of the atmosphere promises is no smaller an

00:20:55.900 --> 00:20:59.250
effort than transforming a city from one centered around the car to

00:20:59.250 --> 00:21:01.080
one centered around the person.

00:21:01.160 --> 00:21:04.300
Just last week, Paris elected a new mayor after 12 years

00:21:04.300 --> 00:21:06.130
of socialist mayor and Hidalgo.

00:21:06.130 --> 00:21:08.000
Mayor Hidalgo's reign ushered in a sle

00:21:08.150 --> 00:21:08.780
w of changes.

00:21:09.100 --> 00:21:12.470
Paris now has a bigger bike network than Amsterdam, thousands of

00:21:12.510 --> 00:21:15.900
new pedestrianized streets, and a whole new public transit line

00:21:15.900 --> 00:21:17.610
that came about around the Olympics.

00:21:17.610 --> 00:21:20.710
While politically controversial at the time, Hidalgo spent 12

00:21:20.830 --> 00:21:23.550
years in office making changes that made Paris more walkable.

00:21:23.710 --> 00:21:25.430
This year, she chose not to run for a third term

00:21:25.460 --> 00:21:25.660
.

00:21:25.660 --> 00:21:28.170
So Paris had the opportunity to maybe reset if they didn't

00:21:28.190 --> 00:21:29.260
like these changes.

00:21:29.370 --> 00:21:32.660
They elected Emmanuel Gregoire, who was her deputy mayor

00:21:32.660 --> 00:21:35.510
for six years and fellow member of the socialist party.

00:21:35.630 --> 00:21:38.870
The city was given an opportunity to vote for a similar party

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:40.080
program and they took it.

00:21:40.080 --> 00:21:42.930
I believe that once people experience the atmosphere and everything it can

00:21:42.930 --> 00:21:45.180
offer, they're going to choose it again and again and

00:21:45.180 --> 00:21:47.440
again, but only if we nail the client experience.

00:21:47.710 --> 00:21:50.740
When you're designing a client experience, you can use just

00:21:50.740 --> 00:21:55.890
four principles to round out the implementation: purpose, safety,

00:21:55.990 --> 00:21:57.100
comfort, and interest.

00:21:57.100 --> 00:22:05.660
Thank you.

00:22:05.660 --> 00:22:14.590
Which of the four do you think is the most

00:22:14.590 --> 00:22:19.320
important to you for sale?

00:22:19.340 --> 00:22:19.660
Yeah.

00:22:19.660 --> 00:22:25.260
For me, the most important is safety and the feel safe

00:22:25.260 --> 00:22:25.500
thing.

00:22:25.590 --> 00:22:27.850
I think people get a lot of value out of having a

00:22:27.850 --> 00:22:31.900
different, calmer, controlled experience and not have to feel

00:22:31.900 --> 00:22:37.180
like they have to do and scroll to keep up with the

00:22:37.310 --> 00:22:37.990
news.

00:22:38.540 --> 00:22:41.870
Yeah, so I was interested in your comment about we need

00:22:41.980 --> 00:22:43.980
to go beyond the theme.

00:22:43.980 --> 00:22:46.710
I feel like a lot of the talks today have really been

00:22:47.160 --> 00:22:53.020
focused around the humanistic elements of the technology and understanding the

00:22:53.020 --> 00:22:55.470
users and meeting them where they are and not saying just for

00:22:55.470 --> 00:22:57.020
granted about that experience.

00:22:57.020 --> 00:23:01.330
I wonder how do you think about balancing trying to push new

00:23:01.330 --> 00:23:05.160
paradigms onto users with kind of leaving them where they

00:23:05.180 --> 00:23:08.410
are, understanding their ideas, like, always that were very

00:23:08.660 --> 00:23:09.260
popular.

00:23:09.320 --> 00:23:13.020
And what do you mean, you're paternalistic about

00:23:13.020 --> 00:23:14.790
, like, no, I know a better way to do

00:23:14.790 --> 00:23:15.740
this or whatever.

00:23:15.740 --> 00:23:16.700
Yeah.

00:23:16.700 --> 00:23:17.100
Yeah.

00:23:17.100 --> 00:23:18.220
No, that's a really good point.

00:23:18.270 --> 00:23:21.170
I loved the -- and to rephrase for the stream

00:23:21.270 --> 00:23:26.590
, to summarize your question, how do we design new experience

00:23:26.620 --> 00:23:29.410
while not being paternalistic about it and just saying,

00:23:29.410 --> 00:23:29.990
"We know better.

00:23:29.990 --> 00:23:33.080
Here's a new design." There was a great session on

00:23:33.080 --> 00:23:36.020
Thursday about user research that -- I don't know if anybody

00:23:36.020 --> 00:23:37.930
in this -- I don't know if any people in this

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:39.860
room were the group that ran it.

00:23:39.860 --> 00:23:41.100
I don't think so.

00:23:41.100 --> 00:23:43.810
But it was really excellent and was a reminder to me that

00:23:43.900 --> 00:23:46.570
we should be basing a lot of our work in user

00:23:46.570 --> 00:23:50.140
research and understanding user needs directly by talking to them.

00:23:50.140 --> 00:23:53.610
It was a great opportunity to do it in the room there

00:23:53.610 --> 00:23:53.750
.

00:23:53.850 --> 00:23:56.790
As a solo founder, I sometimes find it hard to find

00:23:56.790 --> 00:23:58.430
the time for that kind of thing.

00:23:58.590 --> 00:24:01.400
But again, maybe it's another thing we can do collectively

00:24:01.400 --> 00:24:05.230
to figure out what users really want and need from social experiences

00:24:05.230 --> 00:24:05.500
.

00:24:05.500 --> 00:24:11.630
Yeah, I'm building an app called Flux.

00:24:11.750 --> 00:24:12.860
It's, like, a client app.

00:24:12.860 --> 00:24:16.440
And I've similarly been thinking about the sports thing since we

00:24:16.440 --> 00:24:17.640
've seen that take off.

00:24:17.640 --> 00:24:20.300
I'm kind of curious how -- like, how do you

00:24:20.300 --> 00:24:23.560
see that happening with labelers or is there something else?

00:24:23.720 --> 00:24:24.540
Yeah.

00:24:24.540 --> 00:24:31.820
He asked about my idea about like a sports onboarding client

00:24:31.820 --> 00:24:32.070
.

00:24:32.070 --> 00:24:35.110
My full pitch is basically three phases.

00:24:35.230 --> 00:24:37.920
One is just sort of a sign-up onboarding service

00:24:37.920 --> 00:24:40.050
that asks you, "What are your favorite teams?" And

00:24:40.110 --> 00:24:43.060
then this project I thought about building would run some feeds maybe

00:24:43.060 --> 00:24:44.380
on Graze for every team.

00:24:44.380 --> 00:24:47.100
And I maintain, like, a set of Wikipedia scrapers

00:24:47.100 --> 00:24:49.700
or something to get roster data and build the feeds off of

00:24:49.790 --> 00:24:50.590
those keywords.

00:24:50.960 --> 00:24:54.180
And so it would set up your feeds and set up your

00:24:54.180 --> 00:24:57.410
, you know, starter packs based on the league that you

00:24:57.410 --> 00:24:58.770
're interested in.

00:24:59.590 --> 00:25:03.390
Step two would be to then build actually a full client experience

00:25:03.550 --> 00:25:05.670
on top of that specific for sports, right?

00:25:05.790 --> 00:25:07.570
You could layer in live sports data.

00:25:07.570 --> 00:25:09.840
You could layer in, like, highlights.

00:25:09.840 --> 00:25:12.780
You know, do some, you know, fancy algorithm stuff

00:25:12.780 --> 00:25:14.490
to find, like, the big highlight from the game you

00:25:14.740 --> 00:25:15.550
missed or something like that.

00:25:16.780 --> 00:25:19.050
And then step three is, you know, going past the

00:25:19.310 --> 00:25:22.360
live experience, something like fantasy sports on AT Proto or

00:25:22.360 --> 00:25:23.460
something like that.

